# Empirical Framework

## Estimation Strategy

The analysis operates at two levels. The tank-level analysis estimates the effect
of the reform on the closure hazard of individual tanks using both a Cox
proportional hazard model and an OLS linear probability model. The facility-level
analysis estimates the effect on firm behavior: how facilities respond at the
closure margin, whether they change their portfolio composition, and whether
reported leak incidence falls.


### Tank-Level Closure: Cox Proportional Hazard (Primary)

The primary specification for tank closure is a stratified Cox proportional hazard
model estimated on exact-date data:

$$
h_i(t) = h_{0,c(i)}(t) \cdot \exp\!\left(\beta \, D_{it}\right)
$${#eq-cox}

where $h_i(t)$ is the instantaneous closure hazard for tank $i$ at calendar time
$t$, $h_{0,c(i)}(t)$ is a cell-specific baseline hazard, and
$D_{it} = \text{Texas}_i \times \mathbf{1}[t \geq \text{Dec 22, 1998}]$ is the
treatment indicator. Each combination of wall type, fuel type, capacity bin, and
installation cohort receives its own nonparametric baseline hazard through
stratification, with no restriction on how it evolves over time. Standard errors
are clustered at the state level (17 clusters).

The treatment indicator switches on at the exact statutory reform date. Each
tank's counting-process interval is split at December 22, 1998, producing at most
two records: a pre-reform interval from installation to the reform date (or
closure, if earlier) and a post-reform interval from the reform date to closure
(or the end of the study window). All tanks have $D_{it} = 0$ in the pre-reform
interval. Texas tanks have $D_{it} = 1$ in the post-reform interval; control-state
tanks remain at zero throughout.

The coefficient $\beta$ is a log-hazard ratio. $\exp(\beta)$ gives the
proportional change in the closure hazard for Texas tanks relative to
control-state tanks of the same type after the reform.

The Cox model is preferred over OLS for three reasons. First, it conditions on
survival to time $t$. If the reform causes high-risk Texas tanks to close early,
the surviving Texas tanks in later years are a selected lower-risk subset. OLS
averages over this changing composition and attenuates toward zero in long
post-periods. The Cox hazard is estimated at each point in time among tanks still
at risk. Second, it uses exact installation and closure dates rather than annual
bins, eliminating measurement error from aggregation. Third, the stratified
baseline hazard is more flexible than cell-by-year fixed effects. Each cell
receives its own arbitrary time profile; cell-by-year fixed effects impose a
common within-cell intercept shift at annual frequency.

The identifying assumption is that, within each make-model cell, Texas and
control-state tanks would have experienced parallel closure hazards in the absence
of the reform. For example, consider all single-walled gasoline tanks with
capacity between 5,000 and 12,000 gallons installed in 1992. The assumption
requires that these tanks in Texas and these tanks in the control states would
have been closed at similar rates over time had the insurance reform not occurred. The
stratification ensures that any common trend among 1992-vintage single-walled
gasoline tanks of that size is absorbed, and $\beta$ is identified only from the
divergence between Texas and control states within that group after December 1998.


### Tank-Level Closure: OLS Reference Specification

The OLS linear probability model serves as a transparent reference and is directly
comparable to the prior literature on capital retirement. The estimating equation
on the annual tank-year panel is:

$$
Y_{it} = \alpha_i + \gamma_{c(i),t} + \beta \, D_{it}
+ \delta \, A_{it} + \varepsilon_{it}
$${#eq-ols-tank}

where $Y_{it}$ is a binary closure indicator for tank $i$ in year $t$, $\alpha_i$
is a tank fixed effect, $\gamma_{c(i),t}$ is the tank's make-model cell interacted
with calendar year, $D_{it}$ is the treatment indicator defined above, and $A_{it}$
is a time-varying age control (nine three-year bins). Standard errors are clustered
at the state level.

The identifying assumption is the same as for the Cox specification: parallel
trends in the annual closure probability within make-model cells. To continue the
example above, single-walled gasoline tanks of 5,000 to 12,000 gallons installed
in 1992 must have been on the same annual closure trajectory in Texas and in the
control states before the reform. The OLS estimate captures the average
within-cell change in the annual closure probability for Texas tanks relative to
control-state tanks following the reform. As noted above, this estimate attenuates
in the presence of differential survivorship.

Both the Cox and OLS event studies are presented side by side in the results.


### Tank-Level Event Study

The Cox event study replaces the scalar treatment indicator with year-specific
interactions:

$$
h_i(t) = h_{0,c(i)}(t) \cdot \exp\!\left(\sum_{k \neq -1} \beta_k \cdot
\mathbf{1}[K_{it} = k] \cdot \text{Texas}_i\right)
$${#eq-cox-es}

where $K_{it}$ is the year relative to the reform and $k = -1$ is the omitted
reference period. Tails are pooled: years at or below $k = -8$ are collapsed into
one pre-period bin, and years at or above $k = 15$ into one post-period bin. This
stabilizes estimates in years where not all cohorts contribute observations.
Pre-period joint $\chi^2$ tests are reported for the full pre-period and for a
dense window ($k = -6$ to $k = -2$, where all primary cohorts are present).

The OLS event study follows the same pooled-tail structure on the annual panel.
Both event studies are presented together in the results so the reader can compare
the pre-trend evidence and the post-reform dynamics across specifications.


### Facility-Level Behavioral Analysis

The facility-level analysis uses a two-way fixed-effect linear probability model
on the facility-year panel. The baseline specification is:

$$
Y_{jt} = \alpha_j + \gamma_{c(j),t} + \beta \, D_{jt} + \varepsilon_{jt}
$${#eq-fac-base}

where $Y_{jt}$ is a binary or continuous outcome for facility $j$ in year $t$,
$\alpha_j$ is a facility fixed effect, $\gamma_{c(j),t}$ is the facility's
make-model cell interacted with calendar year, and
$D_{jt} = \text{Texas}_j \times \mathbf{1}[t \geq 1999]$. Standard errors are
clustered at the state level (17 clusters). The coefficient $\beta$ captures the
average within-cell change in the outcome for Texas facilities relative to
control-state facilities after the reform.

The interacted specification replaces the scalar treatment with a vector of
interactions:

$$
Y_{jt} = \alpha_j + \gamma_{c(j),t} + \sum_g \beta_g \, D_{jt} \times
\mathbf{1}[G_j = g] + \varepsilon_{jt}
$${#eq-fac-hte}

where $G_j$ is a time-invariant grouping variable measured at the reform date.
When $G_j$ is the facility's wall composition, the $\beta_g$ coefficients give
the treatment effect separately for all-single-walled, all-double-walled, and
mixed-wall facilities. When $G_j$ is the age bin of the oldest tank, the
$\beta_g$ coefficients trace out the treatment effect gradient across the age
distribution.

The identifying assumption for both @eq-fac-base and @eq-fac-hte is that Texas
and control-state facilities in the same make-model cell would have followed
parallel trends in the outcome in the absence of the reform. For example,
consider all-single-walled gasoline-only facilities whose oldest tank was 6 to 8
years old at the reform date. The assumption requires that these facilities in
Texas and their counterparts in the control states would have experienced the same
trend in closure rates, leak rates, or investment behavior had the insurance
reform not occurred. The cell-by-year fixed effects absorb any common time path
within that group, so identification comes only from the divergence between Texas
and control-state facilities of that type after 1999.

Equations @eq-fac-base and @eq-fac-hte are estimated for three groups of outcomes.

**Closure composition.** The unconditional estimates apply @eq-fac-base to the
annual probability of a replacement closure, a permanent closure, and facility
exit. These are the headline causal estimates because they are not conditioned on
any post-treatment variable. A second set applies the same equation to the
subsample of facility-years where a closure occurred, asking whether the reform
shifted the composition of closures. The conditional estimates characterize what
closers did, but the subsample is endogenously selected by treatment. Both sets
are reported.

**Portfolio investment.** Equation @eq-fac-base is applied to net tank count
change, capacity change, new installations, and the probability of a
single-to-double-wall upgrade. A second set conditions on a retrofit occurring
that year.

**Leak incidence.** Equation @eq-fac-base is applied to the total confirmed
release indicator and to each component of the leak decomposition
(closure-revealed, standalone, and known pre-existing). The decomposition
separates mechanical effects of increased closure activity from changes in leak
incidence independent of the closure margin. If the reform increases closures and
the closure-revealed component rises but the standalone component does not, the
reduction in total leaks is mechanical. If the standalone component also falls,
the reform changed actual leak rates.

Equation @eq-fac-hte is applied to the headline outcomes (replacement closure,
exit, single-to-double-wall upgrade, total leaks, and standalone leaks) to trace
the treatment effect gradient across wall type and age.

Facility-level event studies follow the same pooled-tail structure as the
tank-level event studies.


## Threats to Identification

### The Ideal Experiment

The ideal experiment would randomly assign the switch from community rating to
experience rating across otherwise identical states and observe the same
facilities under both regimes. Any post-reform difference in closure rates
between treated and control states would then be attributable to the pricing
regime change without further conditions. Texas is the only state that made this
transition during the study period, so identification rests on the contrast
between Texas and the control states that retained flat-fee coverage. The
make-model design and the tests below are directed at showing that this contrast
is as clean as the available data allow.


### Unobserved Heterogeneity

The primary threat is that Texas and control-state tanks differ on unobserved
characteristics that independently affect closure over this period. The
make-model cell fixed effects address the observable component by restricting
comparisons to tanks of the same wall type, fuel type, capacity, and installation
cohort in the same calendar period. Within a cell, Texas and control tanks faced
the same actuarial risk profile and therefore the same structural premium burden
when private coverage became mandatory. The unit fixed effects $\alpha_i$ absorb
any remaining time-invariant differences at the individual level.

The residual concern is a time-varying shock to Texas that coincides with the
1999 reform and correlates with closure behavior but is unrelated to insurance
pricing. Texas is the only treated state, so any Texas-specific shock in 1999 is
aliased with the treatment effect. Three pieces of evidence address this concern.
First, the event study shows flat pre-trends across the years before the reform
within make-model cells. A confounding shock would need to have left no
pre-period trace and appeared exactly in 1999. Second, the treatment effect is
concentrated among older and single-walled units, where the theory predicts the
largest premium gradient. A general Texas economic shock would produce a uniform
shift across all cell types rather than a gradient that tracks the insurer's rate
schedule. Third, placebo tests treat each control state as if it were treated in
1999 in turn. The Texas estimate lies in the tail of the resulting distribution,
confirming that the post-1999 Texas deviation is unusual relative to what any
single state experiences in a given year.


### Reverse Causality and Anticipation

Reverse causality is not a concern. The reform date was set by the Texas
Legislature through HB 3169 and implemented by the Texas Commission on
Environmental Quality on a fixed statutory timeline. Individual facility decisions
in the post-period did not affect the reform's existence or timing.

The related concern is anticipation. HB 3169 passed in June 1997 with an
18-month implementation window, so owners had advance notice before the December
22, 1998 statutory date. If Texas owners accelerated closures to avoid private
insurance costs, or delayed closures to preserve claims against the expiring fund,
the pre-reform period is not a clean counterfactual. The event study tests for
this directly by examining whether the closure hazard in Texas diverges from the
control states in the years immediately before the statutory date. The event study
results show pre-reform coefficients that are statistically indistinguishable from
zero, and the joint test over the pre-period does not reject the null.


### Measurement Error in Cell Assignment

The cell assignment relies on administrative records for wall construction type
and tank capacity, both of which contain noise. Wall type has a non-trivial
unclassifiable rate in some states, and capacity is rounded or missing for a share
of records. Tanks with missing or unclassifiable attributes are excluded from the
primary sample, as described in Section~\ref{sec-sample-design}. The concern is
that if Texas records are systematically worse than control-state records, the
excluded tanks are disproportionately from Texas and the comparison sample is
unrepresentative.

I address this by comparing the share of unclassifiable and missing-capacity tanks
across states. The data quality table in Appendix~\ref{app-data} shows that the
Texas unknown rates fall within the range of control-state unknown rates.


### Spillovers

The identification strategy requires that the reform's effect on Texas does not
contaminate control-state outcomes. Two spillover channels are plausible. Private
insurers who entered the Texas market may have subsequently expanded into
neighboring control states and changed pricing there. Separately, if the reform
raised demand for tank removal contractors in Texas enough to tighten regional
capacity, neighboring states could face higher removal costs independently of
their own regulatory environment.

I test for border-state contamination by comparing post-1999 closure trends in the
four states bordering Texas (Oklahoma, Arkansas, Louisiana, and New Mexico) to
trends in geographically distant control states. The control-state closure rate
does not change at 1999, which is the direct test for contamination of the control
group.


### The Texas Upgrade Mandate

Texas imposed a phased upgrade mandate under 30 TAC Chapter 334 between 1989 and
1993, requiring existing tanks to meet new construction standards on a rolling
deadline. This mandate mechanically increased closure rates for pre-1989 tanks
during the early 1990s. The primary tank-level sample restricts to tanks installed
between 1989 and 1997, the cohorts built after the mandate was fully enacted and
before the reform date. These tanks were never subject to the mandate's compliance
deadlines, so their pre-reform closure behavior reflects normal retirement
decisions rather than regulatory compliance.



