### Sensitivity to Parallel Trends Violations

@fig-rr-sensitivity reports sensitivity analysis following (Rambachan and Roth,
2023). The method parameterizes parallel trends violations through $M$, the
maximum permitted slope of the pre-trend difference between Texas and the control
group in percentage points per year. The breakdown point is the value of $M$ at
which the lower bound of the robust 95 percent confidence interval for the
average treatment effect on the treated first crosses zero. The largest absolute
slope change observed among the pre-period coefficients at $k = -5$ through
$k = -3$ is 0.0042 percentage points per year. The breakdown point from the
sensitivity analysis is $M = 0.0076$. The result survives parallel trends
violations 1.8 times as large as the maximum deviation observed in the pre-period
data. An unobserved confound would need to generate a trend differential larger
than any present in the pre-reform data to overturn the finding.
```{r}
#| label: fig-rr-sensitivity
#| out-width: "85%"
#| fig-align: center
#| echo: false
#| warning: false
knitr::include_graphics(here::here("Output","Figures","Figure_RR_Sensitivity.pdf"))
```

\vspace{0.2cm}
\begin{flushleft}
\footnotesize
\textit{Notes:} Sensitivity analysis following Rambachan and Roth (2023). The
x-axis is $M$, the maximum permitted slope of a parallel trends violation in
percentage points per year. The shaded region is the robust 95 percent
confidence interval for the average treatment effect on the treated. The blue
dashed line marks the maximum absolute slope change observed among the
pre-period coefficients (0.0042). The grey dotted line marks the breakdown
point (0.0076). The result is robust to violations up to the breakdown value.
\end{flushleft}



# Results {#sec-results}

## Tank Closure Duration

The transition to risk-based insurance raised the rate at which Texas tanks were
retired. @fig-cox-event-study and @fig-ols-event-study present the event study
estimates from the Cox and OLS specifications side by side. In both figures, the
pre-treatment coefficients are close to zero across the full pre-reform window.
The joint $\chi^2$ test of the pre-period coefficients does not reject the null
of parallel pre-trends in either specification ($p = [\text{X}]$ for the Cox full
pre-period; $p = [\text{X}]$ for the dense window). At the reform date the
coefficients turn positive and grow over the post-period, consistent with a
compounding mechanism: as tanks age under risk-based pricing, the annual premium
rises along the rate schedule, so the incentive to close increases over time.

The Cox estimate implies that the reform increased the closure hazard for Texas
tanks by $[\text{X}]$ percent relative to control-state tanks in the same
make-model cell (hazard ratio $= [\text{X}]$, $p = [\text{X}]$). The OLS
estimate on the annual panel is $[\text{X}]$ percentage points ($p = [\text{X}]$),
confirming the direction of the effect. As discussed in Section~\ref{sec-cox-primary},
the OLS estimate is expected to be smaller than what the Cox hazard ratio implies
because survivorship progressively selects lower-risk tanks into the post-period
Texas sample.

@tbl-duration-models reports the full comparison across specifications.

