### Facility-Level Behavioral Analysis

The facility-level analysis uses a two-way fixed-effect linear probability model
on the facility-year panel. The baseline specification is:

$$
Y_{jt} = \alpha_j + \gamma_{c(j),t} + \beta \, D_{jt} + \varepsilon_{jt}
$${#eq-fac-base}

where $Y_{jt}$ is a binary or continuous outcome for facility $j$ in year $t$,
$\alpha_j$ is a facility fixed effect, $\gamma_{c(j),t}$ is the facility's
make-model cell interacted with calendar year, and
$D_{jt} = \text{Texas}_j \times \mathbf{1}[t \geq 1999]$. Standard errors are
clustered at the state level (17 clusters). The coefficient $\beta$ captures the
average within-cell change in the outcome for Texas facilities relative to
control-state facilities after the reform.

The interacted specification replaces the scalar treatment with a vector of
interactions:

$$
Y_{jt} = \alpha_j + \gamma_{c(j),t} + \sum_g \beta_g \, D_{jt} \times
\mathbf{1}[G_j = g] + \varepsilon_{jt}
$${#eq-fac-hte}

where $G_j$ is a time-invariant grouping variable measured at the reform date.
When $G_j$ is the facility's wall composition, the $\beta_g$ coefficients give
the treatment effect separately for all-single-walled, all-double-walled, and
mixed-wall facilities. When $G_j$ is the age bin of the oldest tank, the
$\beta_g$ coefficients trace out the treatment effect gradient across the age
distribution. The identifying assumption for both @eq-fac-base and @eq-fac-hte
is that Texas and control-state facilities in the same make-model cell would have
followed parallel trends in the absence of the reform.
